Euryalus killed Dresus and Opheltius,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\uc0\u8232 then charged after Aesepus and Pedasus,\u8232 whom the naiad nymph Abarbarea bore\u8232 to noble Boucolion, son of high-born Laomedon,\u8232 his eldest son. His mother bore Pedasus in secre\u8232 Bucolion had had sex with the nymph\u8232 while tending to his flock. She became pregnant,\u8232 then gave birth to two twin sons. Euryalus, [30]\u8232 son of Mecistus, slaughtered both of them,\u8232 destroying their strength and splendid bodies.\u8232 Then he stripped the armour from their shoulders.\
Next, fierce warrior Polypoetes killed Astyalus.\uc0\u8232 With his bronze spear Odysseus killed Pidytes from Percote.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 Teucer slaughtered lord Aretaon, and Antilochus,\u8232 Nestor\'92s son, with his glittering spear killed Ableros.\u8232 Agamemnon, king of men, killed Elatus,\u8232 who lived in lofty Pedasus, beside the banks\u8232 of the fair-flowing river Satnioeis. [40]\u8232 Heroic Leitus knocked down Phylacus, as he was fleeing.\u8232 And Eurypylus then slaughtered Melanthus.\
Menelaus, skilled in war cries, took Adrestus still alive.\uc0\u8232 His horses had panicked and bolted off across the plain.\u8232 They charged into a tamarisk bush and snapped the pole\u8232 on the curved chariot, right at the very end.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 The horses then ran off towards the city, where others,\u8232 panic stricken, were headed, too. Adrestus\u8232 rolled out of the chariot beside the wheel,\u8232 face down in the dirt. Menelaus, son of Atreus, [50]\u8232 stood there over him, holding his long-shadowed spear.\u8232 Adrestus clutched Menelaus by the knees and begged:\
\'93Take me alive, son of Atreus\'97you\'92ll get\uc0\u8232 good ransom. My father is a wealthy man,\u8232 owns lots of things\'97bronze, silver, well-worked iron.\u8232 So he\'92ll give you a splendid ransom,\u8232 if he learns I\'92m by Achaean ships, alive.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
Adrestus pleaded. Menelaus\'92 heart in his chest was moved.\uc0\u8232 He was about to hand Adrestus to his attendant,\u8232 to take back captive to the fast Achaean ships. [60]\u8232 But then Agamemnon came running up to him,\u8232 sharply criticizing Menelaus:\
\'93Menelaus, you soft-hearted man,\uc0\u8232 why are you sparing men\'92s lives like this?\u8232 In your own home, Trojans treated you\u8232 exceptionally well, did they not?\u8232 So don\'92t let any one of them evade\u8232 a terrible destruction at our hands\'97\u8232 not even the young child still carried\u8232 in his mother\'92s belly. Let no one escape. [70]\u8232 Let everyone in Troy be slaughtered,\u8232 without pity, without leaving any trace.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
